To change the font for all digits and math symbols in HTML, you can use the CSS `@font-face` rule along with a custom font file that contains the desired font for those characters. Here's an example:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
<style>
@font-face {
  font-family: custom-font;
  src: url(path/to/font-file.ttf);
}

body {
  font-family: custom-font, Arial, sans-serif;
}
</style>
</head>
<body>

<!-- Your HTML content here -->

</body>
</html>
```

In the code above, make sure to replace `path/to/font-file.ttf` with the actual path to your custom font file. This code sets up a custom font family `custom-font` using the `@font-face` rule and then applies that font to the `body` element using the `font-family` property. It also includes fallback fonts like `Arial` and `sans-serif` in case the custom font fails to load. This way, all digits and math symbols will be rendered using the specified custom font.

